		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><BR><font class="h1font"> Dice in Lord of the Rings? Yep!<br></font><font class="bfont"> <b>By:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17'>Neal "Dredlox" Razi</A></font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <table width="100" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" align="right"><tr><td><img src="/lotr/gfx/features/dice.gif" width="140" height="125"><br>
</td></tr><tr valign="top"><td height="114">Editors Note: <br><br>
<font size="1">While doing a quick search on the Internet for dice images I came across some very interesting shops that sell all manner of dice. Brass, Pewter, Bone, Wood you name it. If you like the idea of using dice you should look into getting some that are unique. Just a note!</font></td></tr></table><br>
<br>
Dice in Lord of the Rings?  Yep.<br>
<br>
Dice in card games.  Who would have thunk it?  They bounce, they slide, they just infuriate you.  A lot of questions have been raised about dice in the new Star Wars TCG.  But I&#39;m here to tell you... Dice are your best friend in Lord of the Rings.<br>
<br>
Ok, first, you&#39;re not using Dice for rolling numbers, silly.  They are there to get rid of those hideous counters that plague Lord of the Rings.  That&#39;s right, plague, the seemingly endless counters are really bothersome.  I&#39;m from a Star Wars: CCG background, and we didn&#39;t use nothing other than cards back then, sonny.  But in Lord of the Rings you are going to be stuck with some indicators.  The question becomes &quot;How do you minimize the mess?&quot;<br>
<br>
First, let&#39;s get rid of TWO sets of counters.  Yep, two, with just one die.  These are the burden tokens and the path indicator, two of the more irritating ones.  Here&#39;s what you do: Just get one 10 or 12 side die.  You can get all types of colorful ones, crystal ones, glow in the dark ones for a cost of a whopping 25 cents.  Now use this die as your path indicator, moving it along, and simply rotate the die to the number of burdens you have.  This changes only slowly throughout the game anyway.  This also has the added benefit of being very easy for both you and your opponents to read.<br>
<br>
But there&#39;s more.  You can use dice for wounds as well.  I&#39;ve noticed the counters really have a tendency to scratch up cards plopping on characters, and LOTR is starting to be worth some serious money.  So just use dice and keep them to the side.  6 siders do fine, they are easy to read, and you probably have 50 in your house somewhere.  However, I prefer 4 siders.  They don&#39;t get overturned as easily, and well, they are a little cooler looking.  5 is the highest vitality I&#39;ve seen (Frodo with IB, or Aragron with Saga), so a 4 sider works.  Bring along enough for your fellowship and allies, but don&#39;t use the exact amount or the opponent will know your maximum number of Free People.  No use giving your opponent an advantage.<br>
<br>
Now how about Twilight?  Sorry, here you are stuck with counters.  Twilight just changes TOO much to use dice.  Dice are inconvenient in this regard.<br>
<br>
Finally, in case of a tie in bidding at the start, you don&#39;t have to dig through your pocket for a quarter that will probably land squarely on side smack in the middle of your foil Isildur&#39;s bane dinging it!  Just roll one of your favorites dice.<br>
<br>
So now you know how to lessen your &quot;burden&quot; while playing Lord of the Rings.  Just drop those counters and bring a few dice. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3146&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
